revision.text:
{{refimprove|date=March 2013}} [[File:Hài cốt.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Skulls of victims of the Ba Chúc Massacre]] [[File:Ba Chuc Bone Pagoda - Approach.JPG|thumb|right|300px|Ba Chúc Bone Pagoda - Approach]] [[File:Ba Chuc Bone Pagoda - Detail.JPG|thumb|right|300px|Ba Chúc Bone Pagoda - Detail]] The '''Ba Chúc massacre''' was carried out by the [[Kampuchean Revolutionary Army]] (Khmer Rouge) from April 18 to April 30, 1978 in [[Ba Chúc]], [[Tri Tôn District | Tri Tôn]], [[An Giang Province]], [[Vietnam]]. Of those who had lived in Ba Chúc, 3,157 civilians were killed.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2004/01/07/opinion/07iht-edpringle_ed3_.html "MEANWHILE : When the Khmer Rouge came to kill in Vietnam"] ''New York Times''</ref> Only two survived the massacre. An addition of more than 200 people were killed or injured by land mines deployed by the Khmer Rouge upon retreat.
The attack was one of the events that prompted the [[Cambodian–Vietnamese War|Vietnamese invasion of Kampuchea]].
