In the [[United States]], a '''Form 1099-OID''' is a [[IRS tax forms|tax form]] intended to be submitted to the [[Internal Revenue Service]] by the holder of debt instruments (such as bonds, notes, or certificates) which were discounted at purchase to report the taxable difference between the instruments' actual value and the discounted purchase price.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.irs.gov/pub/irs-pdf/f1099oid.pdf|title=Form 1099-OID|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|website=irs.gov|publisher=Internal Revenue Service|access-date=21 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.irs.gov/publications/p1212/ar02.html|title=Publication 1212 - Main Content|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|website=irs.gov|publisher=Internal Revenue Service|access-date=21 October 2016}}</ref> Like other [[Form 1099|1099 forms]], it is normally filled out by a payer of income (such as an employer) and sent both to tax authorities and the recipient of the income.
==Fraudulent use== [[1099-OID fraud]] consists in filing Form 1099-OID with a false [[withholding tax|withholding]] information to reduce taxable income.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/peterjreilly/2014/08/18/the-oid-fraud-and-criminal-gullibility/#67025a391ff1 |title=The OID Fraud And Criminal Gullibility |author=Peter J. Reilly |date=18 August 2016 |website=Forbes.com |publisher=Forbes, Inc. |access-date=21 October 2016}}</ref> Promoters of the fraud allege that the withheld amount exists in a secret bank account, a claim that originates from the [[redemption movement]]. The IRS has taken notice of 1099-OID fraud schemes and successfully prosecuted them.<ref>[https://www.irs.gov/newsroom/taxpayers-alerted-against-falsely-inflated-refunds-in-dirty-dozen-list-seniors-many-others-at-risk IR-2018-48]</ref>
